INTRODUCTION


  1. Importance of descriptive and inferential data

Both these methods form part of the statistics. Descriptive deals with presenting, organizing, and summarizing the data. It describes only a sample. Descriptive statistics helps us by describing the numbers which are generally required to understand the data.

Inferential statistics is all about getting to a conclusion about the whole data by observing a sample and assuming that all the factors and trends of such sample remains the same throughout. This is very important because it is hard to study huge data.

Example: Group of people collected a sample of water in Indian Ocean and studied it for salt content in the ocean water. Descriptive Statistics: They found that salt contents are 10 parts per thousand in that water. Inferential Statistics: It is impossible to study the whole sea water to get the salt content. Considering the results above and assuming it remains the same across the oceans and other water bodies is a clear example of Inferential Statistics.

  1. Importance of proper data presentation.

We know data is the new oil and if such data is not processed for meaningful results, then it is waste. Hence Proper presentation of data will make it easy to understand, readable, simplified. It also makes the reader feel good going through it and meaningful insights. Example: Having a crude data from the company data base wouldn’t help you fetch the required results and run the analysis. Hence first we must curate the data by cleaning, removing the unwanted information, blanks etc. This will help the data get sorted and segregated and it can be ready for the usage. This curated data now can be processed for clear data, which in turn helps in presentation visually.

  1. Practical Application of R in Data Analysis

R has various data types. R widely used in statistical/data computation. Everyday there are new packages getting added into R, which is making it more powerful for data analysis. We can create objects, operators, and various functions which are available in R will help the users to curate the data and present the visualizations. R is used in data analysis, risk analysis, statistical modeling, customer experience, targeted advertisement, financial reporting, drug testing, clinical trials. Example: Risk analysis is done using R by Lloyds organization. Amazon uses R to provide the product suggestions.

Task 10 


#Explain the differences on data type designations used in R: integer, factor, double, numeric. Perform a search on the Internet to find this information.
#Remember to mention the author and year of your references.

Integer - Integers are part of numerical data without decimals. this form of data will never contain decimals. It is a discrete variable. If there aren’t any decimals in your data, R will automatically consider those as integers. Its command is as.integer()

Factor - Factor data type is nothing but characters but of special kind, just that it has a limited character count. We can know different levels of factor by sing the function levels(). If we need, we can convert the character string into the factor.

Numeric - very frequently used datatype in R is Numeric. It is for storing the numeric data be it either the decimal version or non-decimal. We can check the class of it by class() function. also you can check with Str() to know the structure.

Double - Number data with double precision is is double in R. R represents most of the numbers in double precision which is called as double in R. R coverts single to double data type while executing or computing.

Author - Antoine Soetewey 2019-12-30

Becker, R. A., Chambers, J. M. and Wilks, A. R. (1988) The New S Language. Wadsworth & Brooks/Cole.

Break-even is a situation which needs to be taken care of, else possibility of losing the grip on market and company might not be performing well in the foreseeable future.
  1. When performed the overall analysis on profit, the profit percent is 2%, which is very less for a business to earn. Increasing the marketing frequency and appropriate steps to curb the costs can help the organization not lose the market share and improve profits in the long run.
